{
  "Oxidation is defined as the:": "",
  "Gain of neutrons": "",
  "Loss of electrons": "",
  "Gain of electrons": "",
  "Loss of protons": "",
  "Oxidation means losing electrons. The mnemonic OIL (Oxidation Is Loss) helps remember this. When a species loses electrons, its oxidation number increases.": "",
  "Reduction is defined as the:": "",
  "Gain of protons": "",
  "Loss of mass": "",
  "Reduction means gaining electrons. The mnemonic RIG (Reduction Is Gain) helps. When a species gains electrons, its oxidation number decreases (is 'reduced').": "",
  "In a redox reaction, oxidation and reduction occur:": "",
  "Only oxidation occurs": "",
  "Simultaneously": "",
  "At different times": "",
  "In separate containers": "",
  "In every redox reaction, one species is oxidized while another is simultaneously reduced. Electrons lost by one are gained by the other.": "",
  "The substance that is reduced in a redox reaction is called the:": "",
  "Oxidizing agent": "",
  "Spectator ion": "",
  "Catalyst": "",
  "Reducing agent": "",
  "The oxidizing agent gains electrons (is reduced) and thereby causes another species to be oxidized. It is called 'oxidizing' because it oxidizes the other substance.": "",
  "The substance that is oxidized in a redox reaction is called the:": "",
  "Product": "",
  "Inhibitor": "",
  "The reducing agent loses electrons (is oxidized) and donates them to the oxidizing agent, causing it to be reduced.": "",
  "In Zn + Cu²⁺ → Zn²⁺ + Cu, which species is oxidized?": "",
  "Cu (copper metal)": "",
  "Zn²⁺": "",
  "Cu²⁺ (copper ion)": "",
  "Zn (zinc)": "",
  "Zinc goes from 0 to +2 oxidation state, meaning it lost 2 electrons. Losing electrons = oxidation. Zn is the reducing agent.": "",
  "OIL RIG stands for:": "",
  "Oxidation Is Last, Reduction Is Great": "",
  "Oxygen Is Lost, Reduction Is Gained": "",
  "Oxidation Is Loss, Reduction Is Gain": "",
  "Only Ions Lose, Reactants In Gain": "",
  "OIL RIG is a popular mnemonic: Oxidation Is Loss (of electrons), Reduction Is Gain (of electrons). It helps students remember which process involves which electron change.": "",
  "When an atom's oxidation number increases, the atom has been:": "",
  "Oxidized": "",
  "Reduced": "",
  "Catalyzed": "",
  "Neutralized": "",
  "An increase in oxidation number means the atom lost electrons (became more positive). Losing electrons = oxidation.": "",
  "In the reaction 2Na + Cl₂ → 2NaCl, sodium is:": "",
  "Oxidized (loses an electron to become Na⁺)": "",
  "Reduced (gains an electron)": "",
  "Unchanged": "",
  "Acting as a catalyst": "",
  "Sodium goes from 0 to +1 — it loses one electron per atom. Losing electrons is oxidation. Chlorine gains those electrons (reduction).": "",
  "The oxidation number of any pure, uncombined element is:": "",
  "+1": "",
  "-1": "",
  "0": "",
  "+2": "",
  "By convention, any element in its free, uncombined state (e.g., Fe, O₂, N₂, Na) has an oxidation number of zero.": "",
  "What does 'oxidation number' (oxidation state) represent?": "",
  "The number of bonds an atom forms": "",
  "The apparent charge on an atom in a compound, tracking electron distribution": "",
  "The mass of the atom": "",
  "The number of protons in an atom": "",
  "Oxidation numbers are bookkeeping tools that assign an apparent charge to each atom in a compound, helping track which atoms lose or gain electrons in redox reactions.": "",
  "Define 'oxidizing agent.'": "",
  "The substance that is reduced and causes another substance to be oxidized": "",
  "A substance unchanged by the reaction": "",
  "The substance that is oxidized and donates electrons": "",
  "A substance that prevents oxidation": "",
  "The oxidizing agent accepts electrons (is itself reduced), which forces the other reactant to lose electrons (be oxidized). It 'causes' oxidation in another species.": "",
  "Define 'reducing agent.'": "",
  "The substance that gains electrons": "",
  "The substance that is oxidized and donates electrons to reduce another substance": "",
  "A catalyst that speeds up reduction": "",
  "An inert gas": "",
  "The reducing agent donates electrons (is itself oxidized), supplying the electrons needed for the other species to be reduced.": "",
  "What does the term 'half-reaction' mean in redox chemistry?": "",
  "The point where equilibrium is reached": "",
  "A reaction that is only half complete": "",
  "An equation showing only the oxidation or only the reduction part of a redox reaction": "",
  "A reaction involving half the atoms": "",
  "Half-reactions separate the electron loss (oxidation half) and electron gain (reduction half) so each process can be analyzed independently.": "",
  "What is meant by 'electron transfer' in the context of redox?": "",
  "Neutrons are shared between molecules": "",
  "Energy transfers but no particles move": "",
  "Electrons move from the reducing agent to the oxidizing agent": "",
  "Protons move between atoms": "",
  "Redox reactions fundamentally involve electrons physically moving from one species (reducing agent) to another (oxidizing agent), changing their oxidation states.": "",
  "What does it mean when we say 'reduction IS gain'?": "",
  "The reduced species gains protons": "",
  "The reduced species gains electrons, lowering its oxidation number": "",
  "The reduced species gains energy only": "",
  "The reduced species gains mass": "",
  "Reduction IS Gain of electrons. By gaining negatively charged electrons, the atom's oxidation number decreases — it is 'reduced.'": "",
  "What does 'redox' stand for?": "",
  "Reduction-oxidation": "",
  "Reduced oxygen": "",
  "Reverse oxidation": "",
  "Reactive-deoxidation": "",
  "Redox is a portmanteau of 'reduction' and 'oxidation.' It describes any reaction in which electron transfer occurs between species.": "",
  "Explain what an 'oxidation number change' tells us about a reaction.": "",
  "It measures the mass change": "",
  "It shows the speed of the reaction": "",
  "It tells us the reaction temperature": "",
  "It reveals which atoms lost or gained electrons, confirming a redox reaction": "",
  "Tracking oxidation number changes across a reaction identifies which species were oxidized (number increased) and reduced (number decreased), confirming it is a redox process.": "",
  "What is the meaning of 'disproportionation'?": "",
  "A non-redox reaction": "",
  "A reaction that produces only one product": "",
  "A reaction with unequal masses of reactants": "",
  "A reaction where the same element is both oxidized and reduced": "",
  "Disproportionation is a special redox reaction where atoms of the same element in one substance are simultaneously oxidized and reduced (e.g., 2H₂O₂ → 2H₂O + O₂).": "",
  "Define 'corrosion' as a redox process.": "",
  "The gradual oxidation of a metal by environmental agents like O₂ and water": "",
  "The melting of metal at high temperatures": "",
  "The dissolving of a solid in acid without electron transfer": "",
  "The reduction of a metal ore": "",
  "Corrosion (e.g., rusting of iron) is a slow redox process where metal atoms are oxidized by oxygen and moisture, forming metal oxides or hydroxides.": "",
  "A nail is placed in a beaker of copper sulfate solution. Over time, the nail turns reddish-brown. What happened?": "",
  "The solution changed to iron sulfate without affecting the nail": "",
  "The copper sulfate decomposed": "",
  "Iron in the nail was oxidized, and Cu²⁺ was reduced to copper metal on the nail": "",
  "The nail dissolved without any electron transfer": "",
  "Fe is above Cu in the activity series. Iron is oxidized (Fe → Fe²⁺ + 2e⁻), and Cu²⁺ gains those electrons (Cu²⁺ + 2e⁻ → Cu), depositing reddish copper on the nail.": "",
  "Bleach whitens stains on clothing. In redox terms, what is bleach doing?": "",
  "Neutralizing acids in the stain": "",
  "Acting as an oxidizing agent, oxidizing the colored molecules to colorless ones": "",
  "Acting as a reducing agent": "",
  "Simply dissolving the fabric": "",
  "Bleach (typically sodium hypochlorite) is a strong oxidizing agent. It oxidizes chromophore molecules in the stain, breaking their color-producing bonds.": "",
  "Batteries power flashlights. In a common zinc–carbon battery, zinc is the anode. What happens to zinc?": "",
  "Zinc is oxidized, releasing electrons that flow through the circuit": "",
  "Zinc is reduced and gains electrons": "",
  "Zinc does not participate in the reaction": "",
  "Zinc acts as a catalyst only": "",
  "At the anode, zinc is oxidized (Zn → Zn²⁺ + 2e⁻). Those electrons travel through the external circuit to the cathode, powering the device.": "",
  "An iron bridge is painted to prevent rusting. How does paint protect the iron in redox terms?": "",
  "Paint changes the composition of the iron": "",
  "Paint catalyzes rusting so it happens quickly and stops": "",
  "Paint reduces the iron to a more stable form": "",
  "Paint acts as a barrier, preventing O₂ and H₂O from reaching Fe and oxidizing it": "",
  "Rusting is the oxidation of iron by O₂ and moisture. By coating the surface, paint physically blocks these oxidizing agents from contacting the iron.": "",
  "Photosynthesis converts CO₂ and H₂O into glucose and O₂. Is this a redox process?": "",
  "Yes — CO₂ is reduced to glucose and H₂O is oxidized to O₂": "",
  "No — no electron transfer occurs": "",
  "Yes — but only oxidation occurs": "",
  "No — it is only a synthesis reaction": "",
  "In photosynthesis, carbon in CO₂ is reduced (gains H, loses O) to form glucose, while oxygen in water is oxidized to produce O₂. Both halves of redox are present.": "",
  "A student observes silver tarnish (Ag₂S) forming on silverware exposed to air containing trace H₂S. Identify the redox change for silver.": "",
  "Silver is oxidized from Ag⁰ to Ag⁺ in Ag₂S": "",
  "Silver is reduced": "",
  "No redox occurs — tarnishing is physical": "",
  "Silver acts as a reducing agent for oxygen": "",
  "Ag⁰ → Ag⁺ represents a loss of electrons (oxidation). The sulfur in H₂S is reduced, gaining electrons from silver as tarnish (Ag₂S) forms.": "",
  "Galvanizing steel involves coating it with zinc. If the coating is scratched, the zinc corrodes instead of the steel. Why?": "",
  "Zinc reduces the iron chemically": "",
  "The scratch seals the steel from oxygen": "",
  "Zinc is more reactive (easily oxidized) than iron, so it sacrificially corrodes first": "",
  "Zinc is more resistant to oxidation than iron": "",
  "Zinc is higher than iron on the activity series, so it is preferentially oxidized. This 'sacrificial' oxidation protects the underlying iron from rusting.": "",
  "In cellular respiration, glucose is broken down: C₆H₁₂O₆ + 6O₂ → 6CO₂ + 6H₂O. What is oxidized and what is reduced?": "",
  "Nothing is oxidized or reduced": "",
  "Glucose (carbon) is oxidized; oxygen is reduced": "",
  "Water is oxidized; CO₂ is reduced": "",
  "Oxygen is oxidized; carbon is reduced": "",
  "Carbon in glucose goes from a low oxidation state to +4 in CO₂ (oxidized). Oxygen goes from 0 in O₂ to -2 in H₂O and CO₂ (reduced).": "",
  "A student tests two metals: magnesium vigorously reacts with dilute HCl, but copper shows no reaction. What does this reveal about their relative reducing ability?": "",
  "Neither undergoes redox with HCl": "",
  "Both are equally reactive": "",
  "Copper is a stronger reducing agent": "",
  "Magnesium is a stronger reducing agent (more easily oxidized) than copper": "",
  "Mg is above H in the activity series, so it displaces H₂ from HCl (Mg is oxidized). Cu is below H and cannot displace it, showing Cu is a weaker reducing agent.": "",
  "A fruit turns brown when cut and exposed to air. This browning involves the oxidation of phenols. Adding lemon juice (vitamin C) prevents browning. What role does vitamin C play?": "",
  "Vitamin C causes the phenols to decompose": "",
  "Vitamin C is an oxidizing agent that speeds browning": "",
  "Vitamin C is a reducing agent that donates electrons, preventing oxidation of phenols": "",
  "Vitamin C has no redox role — it only changes pH": "",
  "Vitamin C (ascorbic acid) is a powerful reducing agent — it sacrificially donates electrons, being oxidized itself to prevent the phenol compounds from oxidizing (browning).": ""
